{"page_content": "Single-agent systems\nA single agent can handle many tasks by incrementally adding tools, keeping complexity \nmanageable and simplifying evaluation and maintenance. Each new tool expands its capabilities \nwithout prematurely forcing you to orchestrate multiple agents.\nTools\nGuardrails\nHooks\nInstructions\nAgent\nInput\nOutput\nEvery orchestration approach needs the concept of a \u2018run\u2019, typically implemented as a loop that \nlets agents operate until an exit condition is reached. Common exit conditions include tool calls, \u2028\na certain structured output, errors, or reaching a maximum number of turns.\u00a0\n14\nA practical guide to building agents", "metadata": {"producer": "pdf-lib (https://github.com/Hopding/pdf-lib)", "creator": "pdf-lib (https://github.com/Hopding/pdf-lib)", "creationdate": "2025-04-07T14:20:51+00:00", "source": "D:\\Users\\wpoga\\Documents\\Ebooks\\Artificial Intelligence\\a-practical-guide-to-building-agents.pdf", "file_path": "D:\\Users\\wpoga\\Documents\\Ebooks\\Artificial Intelligence\\a-practical-guide-to-building-agents.pdf", "total_pages": 34, "format": "PDF 1.7", "title": "", "author": "", "subject": "", "keywords": "", "moddate": "2025-04-07T14:20:54+00:00", "trapped": "", "modDate": "D:20250407142054Z", "creationDate": "D:20250407142051Z", "page": 13}, "type": "Document"}
